solution.p:
There are many ways to make graphs that distinguish these centrality measures from one another. But it is true that in real world networks, these quantities tend to be correlated. The example networks below are variants of a simple idea. A barbell graph is a graph that consist of two complete graphs K_s and K_t connected by a path of length r.




\begin{tikzpicture} %mathbook width=90%

\draw[thick] (0,0) circle (.75);

\draw[thick] (8,0) circle (1.5);

\draw[thick]   (.75,0) -- (6.5,0);

\draw [decoration={brace,raise=3mm,amplitude=16pt, mirror},decorate]   (.75,0) -- (6.5,0);


\node at (0,0) {K};
\node at (.2,-.15) {\scriptsize s};
\node at (8,0) {K};
\node at (8.2,-.15) {\scriptsize t};

\node at (3.75,-1.25) {P};
\node at (3.95,-1.4) {\scriptsize r};

\end{tikzpicture}




Sometimes we take s=t and sometimes we take s \ll t. Likewise, sometimes r \approx s and sometimes r \gg s. We will make some rough calculations below (rather than getting them exactly right) to compare the sizes of our measures.










 High Degree and Low Closeness.   Consider a graph consisting of two large cliques (complete graphs) of the same size connected by a long path. We call this a barbell graph. Vertices in the two cliques have high degree, but have low closeness because almost half of the vertices are far away. Here is an example



\begin{tikzpicture} %mathbook width=90%

\draw[thick] (0,0) circle (.75);

\draw[thick] (8,0) circle (.75);

\draw[thick]   (.75,0) -- (7.25,0);

\draw [decoration={brace,raise=3mm,amplitude=16pt, mirror},decorate]   (.75,0) -- (7.25,0);


\node at (0,0) {K};
\node at (.25,-.15) {\scriptsize 10};

\node at (8,0) {K};
\node at (8.25,-.15)  {\scriptsize 10};

\node at (4,-1.25) {P};
\node at (4.3,-1.4)  {\scriptsize 101};

\draw[fill] (.75,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (4,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (8.75,0) circle (3pt);

\node[above right] at (.75,0) {a};
\node[above right] at (4,0) {b};
\node[above right] at (8.75,0) {c};

\end{tikzpicture}




High degree: c_a^C = 10, which is the maximum degree. There are many vertices with degree 2.

Low closeness:

{1/c_a^C} = 9 + \sum_{i=1}^{100} i +   9 \times 101 = 5968.

Meanwhile,

{1/c_b^C}  = 2 \left( \sum_{i=1}^{50} i + 9 \times 51 \right)
= 50 \times 51 + 18 \times 51 = 3468.

So c_a^C \approx 0.58 C_b^C.

In the graph above, we have c_c^D = k_c = 9 which is just one below the maximum degree. However c_c^B=0.









 High Degree and Low Betweenness.


Consider the same barbell graph from the previous example. The degree of the vertices in the cliques are very high, yet all but one of them have 0 betweenness. The vertices on the path connecting the two cliques have higher betweenness.








 High Closeness and Low Degree.

Once again, the barbell graph above provides an example. The center of the graph has the largest closeness, but has degree 2.







 High Closeness and Low Betweenness.   This one is a little trickier. How can you be close to everything, but not located on shortest paths? The answer: add a leaf to a vertex with high closeness. For example we add a leaf d to the central vertex b of the barbell graph.

This vertex d has relatively large closeness. We have

\frac{1}{c_d^C} = 121 + \frac{1}{c_b^C},

because this vertex is just one step further than c to the rest of the graph. So c_d^C \approx 0.98 c_b^C. Meanwhile c_d^B=0.



\begin{tikzpicture} %mathbook width=90%

\draw[thick] (0,0) circle (.75);

\draw[thick] (8,0) circle (.75);

\draw[thick]   (.75,0) -- (7.25,0);

\draw[thick]   (4,0) -- (4,.5);

\draw [decoration={brace,raise=3mm,amplitude=16pt, mirror},decorate]   (.75,0) -- (7.25,0);


\node at (0,0) {K};
\node at (.25,-.15) {\scriptsize 10};

\node at (8,0) {K};
\node at (8.25,-.15)  {\scriptsize 10};

\node at (4,-1.25) {P};
\node at (4.3,-1.4)  {\scriptsize 101};

\draw[fill] (.75,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (4,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (8.75,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (4,.5) circle (3pt);

\node[above right] at (.75,0) {a};
\node[above right] at (4,0) {b};
\node[above right] at (8.75,0) {c};
\node[above left] at (4, .5) {d};

\end{tikzpicture}










 High Betweenness and Low Degree.
Once again, the barbell graph does the trick. The central vertex b has the largest betweenness, but it only has degree 2.







 High Betweenness and Low Closeness.
Another tricky one. How can you be between lots of vertices, yet not have a high closeness value?
Let's look at a barbell graph where the cliques are of very different sizes.



\begin{tikzpicture} %mathbook width=90%

\draw[thick] (0,0) circle (.75);

\draw[thick] (8.75,0) circle (1.5);

\draw[thick]   (.75,0) -- (7.25,0);

\draw [decoration={brace,raise=3mm,amplitude=16pt, mirror},decorate]   (.75,0) -- (7.25,0);


\node at (0,0) {K};
\node at (.25,-.15) {\scriptsize 11};

\node at (8.75,0) {K};
\node at (9.15,-.15)  {\scriptsize 1001};

\node at (4,-1.25) {P};
\node at (4.3,-1.4)  {\scriptsize 101};

\draw[fill] (.75,0) circle (3pt);
\draw[fill] (7.25,0) circle (3pt);

\node[above right] at (.75,0) {a};
\node[above left] at (7.25,0) {b};

\end{tikzpicture}


In this graph, most vertices have zero betweenness. We have

c_a^B = 10 \times 1100 = 11000.

and

{1/c_a^C} = 10 + \sum_{i=1}^{100} i + 101 \times 1000 = 106060.

Meanwhile
the closeness of node b is

{1/c_b^B} = 1000 + \sum_{i=1}^{100} i + 101 \times 10 = 7060.

